      },
      "date": "2023-05-16 08:12:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nI'm working on a patch to remove the gssd fork completely, just keeping gss keyring, sk keyring and lsvcgssd. \nHopefully I will find some time to finish that.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5693ad85c4f57d4341a25c34ba2aeddc181802b9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2023-05-19 10:41:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThat's the patch I was talking about: https://review.whamcloud.com/c/fs/lustre-release/+/51032",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "9acf723a539e6a00d5ea21a707dec268ce955ecd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 931,
        "name": "Timothy Day",
        "email": "timday@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "timday"
      },
      "date": "2023-05-19 16:47:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> That's the patch I was talking about: https://review.whamcloud.com/c/fs/lustre-release/+/51032\n\nDo you know the history behind the lgssd fork? Why did the fork need to exist?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a3524a63fea0ece85e7f114d6c605846506f3999",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 793,
        "name": "Aurelien Degremont",
        "email": "adegremont@nvidia.com",
        "username": "degremoa"
      },
      "date": "2023-05-22 09:49:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> Do you know the history behind the lgssd fork? Why did the fork need to exist?\n\nI tried to understand why, but did not find a clear explanation. Could only tell this is no more used. That's how NFS KRB was working, and Lustre just did it the same way, even simply patching it. There is some differences like the principal name is not the same, the pipe path should also not conflict with NFS one. Lustre also has 3 services (mgs, mds, oss) whereas nfs only has one. They are probably some other differences. Looks they eventually decided to fork it instead of maintaining a patch that would have been harder and harder to maintian over time.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
